SubTopics: Model chromosome progression through meiosis and fertilization in order to argue how the processes of sexual reproduction lead to both genetic similarities and variation in diploid organisms. Compare and contrast the processes of sexual and asexual reproduction, identifying the advantages and disadvantages of each.
Content: Which statement describes an advantage of sexual reproduction over asexual reproduction?

M.Choice: Sexual reproduction results in more genetic variation in organisms than asexual reproduction.

P.Choice: Sexual reproduction requires more time to produce organisms than asexual reproduction.

R.Choice: Sexually produced offspring are more dependent on their parents for survival than offspring produced through asexual reproduction.

S.Choice: Sexually produced organisms are more dependent on other organisms for reproduction than offspring produced through asexual reproduction.

SubTopics: Analyze through research the cycling of matter in our biosphere and explain how biogeochemical cycles are critical for ecosystem function.
Content: In an investigation into the role of plants in the cycling of matter, a researcher is designing an experiment in which plants will be grown under conditions that will limit the rate of photosynthesis. Which design would match the goal of the researcher?

M.Choice: Grow the plants in a low oxygen environment and measure the rate of carbon dioxide production.

P.Choice: Grow the plants in a low carbon dioxide environment and measure the rate of oxygen production.

R.Choice: Grow the plants in soil containing excess water and measure the rate of transpiration.

S.Choice: Grow the plants in soil containing excess nitrogen and measure the rate of plant growth.

SubTopics: Utilize a model of a cell plasma membrane to compare the various types of cellular transport and test predictions about the movement of molecules into or out of a cell based on the homeostasis of energy and matter in cells.
Content: Dialysis bags can be used as models of cells to explore the movement of materials into and out of cells.

Students set up an investigation with a dialysis bag containing a 2% iodine solution in a beaker containing a 9% starch solution as shown in the figure. Starch turns blue-black in the presence of iodine. The dialysis bag is permeable to water and iodine but not to starch.
